{{Third-party|date=September 2017}}
{{italictitle}} '''''Spike Art Quarterly''''', also known as '''''Spike Art Magazine''''' or simply '''''Spike''''', is a [[bilingual]] ([[German language|German]] and [[English language|English]]) [[contemporary art]] magazine published in print four times a year with new content published online weekly. ''Spike'' was founded in [[Vienna]], [[Austria]] in 2004 by artist Rita Vitorelli.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shop.gudbergnerger.com/collections/magazines/products/spike-art-quarterly-51|title=Spike Art Quarterly #51|website=Gudberg Nerger|language=en|access-date=2017-09-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.spikeartmagazine.com/en/about-us|title=About us|date=2014-07-28|work=Spike Art Magazine|access-date=2017-09-06|language=en}}</ref>
In 2014, along with the redesign by [[:de:Mirko_Borsche|Mirko Borsche]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bureauborsche.com/projects/spike-no-42|title=Spike Issue No. 42|last=Borsche|first=Bureau|website=bureauborsche.com|access-date=2017-09-06}}</ref> Spike opened a second editorial office and a [[non-commercial]] [[art space]] in [[Berlin]] where it now hosts regular events, including their round-table [[discussions]], as well as [[Lecture|lectures]], talks and [[performances]]. Their offices in Berlin are located opposite the [[Volksbühne]] on [[Rosa-Luxemburg-Platz]] in [[Mitte]].
The magazine has had contributions from the following [[art critics]]: [[Karen Archey]], [[Pablo León de la Barra]], [[Alison M. Gingeras]], [[Bruce Hainley]] and [[Hans-Ulrich Obrist]].
